author: @eaudesolero5631
text: ok, so, this method creates a network of nodes, collected in layers, which are connected to nodes only in the layer next to it on either side, before and after, if you will. however our brains are more complexly connected.  is there anyone who has attempted this in software? it'd be a fairly simple extension of the nested looping matrices. either way let's look at that here.  though i should note that the brain does have structures, subsets of collected neurons connected in seeming repeated common patterns, used for certain kinds of functionality.    i.e. we need several of these different more complexly internally connected models then connected to each other  but this will obviously increase the computation significantly, so will probably need to be implemented in a more efficient language, compiled instead of interpretive, like c or rust.

author: @DanKaschel
text: I just bought the textbook! This is a great series and is just the kind of ground-up education I was looking for.   One thing I'm struggling with in the textbook is that, in preparation for backpropogation, you spend a ton of time on mathematical fundamentals. As someone who hasn't touched calculus in 15 years, it's a slog and the mathematical notation is hard to get used to. I get that it's a necessary evil, but I don't think the textbook does a great job of contextualizing the information. In this video, I followed why random and incremental permutation were too inefficient, but I don't really follow how the derivative is used here.  I think I lack the intuition for what it means that the network can be represented as a single equation (probably because I'm used to thinking algorithmically). So, while I know what a derivative is, I don't really understand what it means to take a derivative of a neural network.   I expect all that will come with time, BUT it's a momentum killer to have all this hard-to-digest theory in an unfamiliar notation without a clear sense of how it will help.

author: @DRealHammer
text: edit: just noticed, someone already mentioned this, but maybe the explanation is appreciated by someone  Cool video, just a little inaccuracy: You mentioned at 8:16: "this can only be done on a continuous curve, so no sharp corners"  I know this is an introduction but to clarify: a continuous function can have sharp corners. A better description for a continuous function would be that it should be " connected", so no parts, where it suddenly jumps from 1 to 0 without a connection. Someone gave an intuition like "if you can draw it without lifting your pencil it's continuous. But there's a bit more to it.  what we want to look at are "differentiable function", so functions you can differentiate (or find a derivative). Does not help with understanding, but these are the functions with no sharp corners. All differentiable functions are continuous. So it is a stronger statement.  Examples: f(x) = x^2 is differentiable and hence also continuous  f(x) = abs(x) is continuous, but no differentiable (sharp corner at 0, as the function describes a V shape)  f(x) = 1, if 0 < x < 1; else 0 is not continuous, hence also not differentiable (we have value jumps at x = 0 and x = 1)

author: @i4ko95
text: https://youtu.be/txh3TQDwP1g?t=496 "This can only be done on a continuous curve, so no sharp corners..." Sharp corners are allowed to exist on continuous curves. What you meant to say is "non differentiable", meaning that the derivative as defined with limits is not defined there.  I get that this is not really appropriate for a higher-level technical explanation. So I guess saying "no sharp corners are not allowed" is fine.  P.S.: Great visuals!
